<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-328-718  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 328 718.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Seybold Report on Desktop Publishing  April 2 1990 v4 n8p37(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Publications Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Xerox-Apple suit largely dismissed. (The latest word)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Xerox Corp. (cases)Apple Computer Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; XRX.andO;Topic:     User InterfaceComputer IndustryCopyright.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Xerox-Apple suit largely dismissed A federal judge has dismissed criticalportions of the lawsuit Xerox filed against Apple last December.andP;  The suitalleged that Apple had made unlawful use of copyrighted portions of the XeroxStar user interface (see Vol.andP;  4, No.andP;  5, page 24).andP;  Although Xerox could getthe ruling reversed on appeal, it now looks as if the entire user-interfacelegal circus may simply peter out.andM;Apple, if you recall, started the affair by suing Microsoft andHewlett-Packard for infringing the Macintosh user interface.andP;  That suit wasemasculated when the judge ruled that Microsoft did have rights to most ofthe user interface under the terms of its earlier license agreement withApple.andP;  Meanwhile, Xerox sued Apple, claiming that Apple based the userinterface for its Lisa and Macintosh computers on work originally done byXerox, and that if anyone &quot;owned&quot; the concepts it was Xerox and not Apple.andM;On Friday, March 23, U.S.andP;  District Judge Vaughn Walker dismissed five of sixcounts of the Xerox suit against Apple.andP;  The judge ruled that Xerox does nothave standing to pursue its case.andP;  The only count remaining is one that asksfor a declaratory judgment that Xerox is the owner of copyrights it filed inconjunction with its Star workstation.andM;While Xerox would probably consider such a judgment a moral victory, it isnot likely that it would be able to collect any financial damages now thatthe rest of the case has been thrown out.andM;Xerox says that it will appeal the ruling.andO;</TEXT></DOC>